Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a table in LaTeX that redacts the text in the input using black boxes. The table will display the specified text as a series of black boxes.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{array}
\usepackage{graphicx}

% Custom command to create a black box
\newcommand{\blackbox}{\rule{0.3cm}{0.3cm}}

% Function to generate redacted text
\newcommand{\redact}[1]{
  \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5}
  \begin{tabular}{|c|}
    \hline
    \parbox{\linewidth}{\centering\strut
      \foreach \n in {1,...,#1} {\blackbox\ }
    } \\
    \hline
  \end{tabular}
}

\begin{document}

% Example usage
\redact{5} \redact{7} \redact{25} \redact{5}

\end{document}
```

In this code snippet:
- The `\blackbox` command is defined to create a small black square.
- The `\redact` command takes a number as input, which represents the number of black boxes to create.
- In the example usage, the input "Private medical information should not be shared widely" is replaced with the sequence of calls `\redact{5} \redact{7} \redact{25} \redact{5}` to generate the redacted text in a tabular format.

Compile this code in a LaTeX editor to see the result. Each phrase or sentence that you want to redact should be represented by a separate call to `\redact` with the appropriate number of black boxes.
